00:14:03.880 --> 00:14:06.630
We have to learn from these outcomes.

00:14:06.630 --> 00:14:08.290
We have to learn from these tragedies

00:14:08.290 --> 00:14:11.120
to get a better response and to prevent

00:14:11.120 --> 00:14:15.533
subsequent catastrophic
failures as this one was.

00:14:16.550 --> 00:14:17.833
So how do we get better?

00:14:19.340 --> 00:14:22.060
Better discernment, as we call it

00:14:22.060 --> 00:14:24.320
in law enforcement, situational awareness.

00:14:24.320 --> 00:14:26.710
Knowing what you have in front of you.

00:14:26.710 --> 00:14:28.210
That only comes with training.

00:14:29.310 --> 00:14:31.120
So to get better in discernment,

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:35.220
one of the avenues where the San Francisco

00:14:35.220 --> 00:14:37.150
Police Department is really focusing on

00:14:37.150 --> 00:14:41.070
is identifying and being
able to distinguish

00:14:41.070 --> 00:14:43.593
a person in a mental health crisis

00:14:43.593 --> 00:14:47.930
versus a person with a disability

00:14:47.930 --> 00:14:50.183
that's causing this type of response.

00:14:51.580 --> 00:14:53.890
Unlike incidents involving a person

00:14:53.890 --> 00:14:56.104
in a mental or physical crisis,

00:14:56.104 --> 00:14:58.770
there's really not been
a concentrated focus on

00:14:58.770 --> 00:15:02.220
specifically addressing
persons with an intellectual,

00:15:02.220 --> 00:15:04.540
developmental disability
in law enforcement.

00:15:04.540 --> 00:15:06.730
And although the current
training to respond

00:15:06.730 --> 00:15:10.079
to persons in crisis is fairly effective,

00:15:10.079 --> 00:15:12.300
we need to recognize
that although similar,

00:15:12.300 --> 00:15:14.300
there is a big difference,
a marked difference,

00:15:14.300 --> 00:15:16.720
between persons considered
in a mental health

00:15:16.720 --> 00:15:20.170
or health crisis and
those with an intellectual

00:15:20.170 --> 00:15:22.710
or developmental disability,
and that these differences

00:15:22.710 --> 00:15:25.556
may require a different response.

00:15:25.556 --> 00:15:29.030
And going back to Ethan's situation,

00:15:29.030 --> 00:15:31.360
I don't know what training
those officers had,

00:15:31.360 --> 00:15:35.320
and it's not fair for me
to judge them on that,

00:15:35.320 --> 00:15:39.480
but what I do know is in those situations,

00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:40.980
the better training you have,

00:15:40.980 --> 00:15:42.690
the better understanding you have,

00:15:42.690 --> 00:15:45.350
the better off you are
in terms of dealing with

00:15:45.350 --> 00:15:48.550
and effectively handling those encounters.

00:15:48.550 --> 00:15:51.140
As a result of Ethan's
incident, the Maryland governor

00:15:51.140 --> 00:15:52.730
created a commission and developed

00:15:52.730 --> 00:15:55.440
a statewide training
standard for law enforcement

00:15:55.440 --> 00:15:58.141
in Maryland and first
responders to interact

00:15:58.141 --> 00:16:00.483
with people with disabilities.

00:16:04.370 --> 00:16:08.450
So, how do we distinguish
persons in crisis

00:16:08.450 --> 00:16:10.303
versus developmental disabilities?

00:16:11.140 --> 00:16:14.970
First, let me start with
what the definition of those.

00:16:14.970 --> 00:16:17.849
A situation in which a person experiences

00:16:17.849 --> 00:16:21.830
an intensive behavioral, emotional,

00:16:21.830 --> 00:16:26.620
or psychiatric response triggered
by a precipitating event.

00:16:26.620 --> 00:16:28.740
I'm sorry, can't even say the word.

00:16:28.740 --> 00:16:31.017
That's a health crisis.

00:16:31.017 --> 00:16:33.670
You know, the person
may be at risk of harm

00:16:33.670 --> 00:16:35.650
to self or others, disoriented,

00:16:35.650 --> 00:16:38.070
or out of touch with reality,
functionally compromised,

00:16:38.070 --> 00:16:42.110
and otherwise agitated,
unable to be calmed down.

00:16:42.110 --> 00:16:43.960
If the crisis is left untreated,

00:16:43.960 --> 00:16:46.430
it can result in a
mental health emergency.

00:16:46.430 --> 00:16:49.300
Now, we come in contact,
particularly in the city

00:16:49.300 --> 00:16:52.480
and county of San Francisco,
we come in contact

00:16:52.480 --> 00:16:54.533
with this situation quite a bit.

00:16:57.450 --> 00:17:01.020
You know, these incidents
can lead to suicide

00:17:01.020 --> 00:17:03.320
due to depression, a lot of times.

00:17:03.320 --> 00:17:06.266
They're really aggravated
by substance abuse,

00:17:06.266 --> 00:17:10.250
by untreated psychiatric
disorders, PTSD, et cetera.

00:17:10.250 --> 00:17:14.020
There's a large spectrum of
issues that we come across.

00:17:14.020 --> 00:17:18.160
But there's really a
need to understand that

00:17:18.160 --> 00:17:22.860
as opposed to a person
who's intellectually

00:17:22.860 --> 00:17:27.540
or developmentally disabled,
and that disability

00:17:27.540 --> 00:17:28.940
is what's driving the behavior,

00:17:28.940 --> 00:17:32.790
as opposed to a crisis caused
by psychosis from drugs

00:17:32.790 --> 00:17:35.730
or some other mental health breakdown.

00:17:35.730 --> 00:17:37.210
It's really important to discern,

00:17:37.210 --> 00:17:39.420
because our response
can be the difference,

00:17:39.420 --> 00:17:41.486
as we saw in the last video,
between life and death.

00:17:41.486 --> 00:17:44.263
It's that serious for us.

00:17:45.847 --> 00:17:50.070
The definition of intellectual disability:

00:17:50.070 --> 00:17:53.090
these disorders are
characterized by limited

00:17:53.090 --> 00:17:56.852
mental capacity and difficulty
with adaptive behaviors,

00:17:56.852 --> 00:17:58.950
behaviors such as
managing money, schedules,

00:17:58.950 --> 00:18:01.030
routines, social interactions.

00:18:01.030 --> 00:18:03.050
They generally appear
before the age of 18,

00:18:03.050 --> 00:18:06.460
and may result from physical
causes such as autism,

00:18:06.460 --> 00:18:10.140
cerebral palsy, or from
non-physical causes such as

00:18:10.140 --> 00:18:13.300
a lack of stimulation
and adult responsiveness.

00:18:13.300 --> 00:18:16.130
Developmental disabilities,
severe long-term disabilities

00:18:16.130 --> 00:18:18.270
that can affect cognitive abilities,

00:18:18.270 --> 00:18:20.550
physical functioning, or both.

00:18:20.550 --> 00:18:23.300
Now generally they appear
before the age of 22

00:18:23.300 --> 00:18:25.853
and are likely to be lifelong.

00:18:27.100 --> 00:18:30.270
Here is a tip, and I wanna
go back to this video

00:18:30.270 --> 00:18:33.349
that we saw a second ago
with Ethan, with the aide.

00:18:33.349 --> 00:18:35.270
The aide that was there to help,

00:18:35.270 --> 00:18:37.450
the aide that was there
to give information that,

00:18:37.450 --> 00:18:40.450
had it been listened
to, may have prevented

00:18:40.450 --> 00:18:43.030
that situation from escalating,

00:18:43.030 --> 00:18:46.640
one of the things that
it's sometimes difficult

00:18:46.640 --> 00:18:49.040
for police officers to do,
particularly in the heat

00:18:49.040 --> 00:18:52.990
of the moment, is slow down.

00:18:52.990 --> 00:18:55.000
Slow down and listen.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:57.800
And oftentimes we get in the situation

00:18:57.800 --> 00:19:00.770
where we believe
somebody's life is at risk,

00:19:00.770 --> 00:19:03.040
or safety is at risk, and it's all about

00:19:03.040 --> 00:19:05.850
stabilizing the situation,
but we've learned over time,

00:19:05.850 --> 00:19:08.320
particularly those of us
that've been around for a while,

00:19:08.320 --> 00:19:09.580
that we have to step back,

00:19:09.580 --> 00:19:11.920
and we really do have to slow things down.

00:19:11.920 --> 00:19:13.590
And we're gonna talk a little bit more

00:19:13.590 --> 00:19:16.253
in future slides about
how we are doing that.

00:19:17.361 --> 00:19:19.390
Getting back to some of the signs

00:19:19.390 --> 00:19:21.440
of developmental disability.

00:19:21.440 --> 00:19:23.120
Some people may be solely physical,

00:19:23.120 --> 00:19:24.633
such as blindness from birth.

00:19:25.477 --> 00:19:29.610
Others may involve physical
and intellectual disabilities

00:19:29.610 --> 00:19:32.200
stemming from a genetic or other causes

00:19:32.200 --> 00:19:36.039
such as Down syndrome or
fetal alcohol syndrome.

00:19:36.039 --> 00:19:41.039
There's a characteristic that I learned,

00:19:42.490 --> 00:19:45.350
particularly from my personal
experience with our son.

00:19:45.350 --> 00:19:48.490
When he was younger, there
were no outward signs

00:19:48.490 --> 00:19:49.323
that he was disabled.

00:19:49.323 --> 00:19:50.750
He looked like a normal child.

00:19:50.750 --> 00:19:53.808
And as soon as you interacted with him,

00:19:53.808 --> 00:19:56.960
you could quickly figure out
that that wasn't the case,

00:19:56.960 --> 00:20:01.960
but there is a population
out there of many people

00:20:02.750 --> 00:20:06.870
that are intellectually and
developmentally disabled

00:20:06.870 --> 00:20:11.870
where on first appearance,
you can't tell the difference.

00:20:12.130 --> 00:20:14.950
That's a much harder population for,

00:20:14.950 --> 00:20:16.800
particularly for law enforcement officers,

00:20:16.800 --> 00:20:20.160
because you really have to know

00:20:20.160 --> 00:20:21.350
what you're looking for, number one.

00:20:21.350 --> 00:20:23.120
You really have to know
the cues, number two.

00:20:23.120 --> 00:20:24.550
Number three, you really
have to be trained.

00:20:24.550 --> 00:20:27.152
If you don't have a personal
experience like I do,

00:20:27.152 --> 00:20:29.910
you really have to
understand and know that

00:20:29.910 --> 00:20:32.318
just because a person looks
like a typical individual,

00:20:32.318 --> 00:20:34.490
they may not be.

00:20:34.490 --> 00:20:37.610
And that processing has
to happen pretty quickly

00:20:37.610 --> 00:20:39.630
in a volatile situation.

00:20:39.630 --> 00:20:41.060
This is why we have to train.

00:20:41.060 --> 00:20:44.440
This is why it's so
important to have videos

00:20:44.440 --> 00:20:46.110
like what Captain Moore put together,

00:20:46.110 --> 00:20:49.853
so our officers have an
awareness of what to look for.

00:20:54.120 --> 00:20:55.830
I'm gonna segue into use of force,

00:20:55.830 --> 00:20:58.920
because oftentimes, when we
don't know what to look for,

00:20:58.920 --> 00:21:03.420
those encounters turn
into what we don't want,

00:21:03.420 --> 00:21:05.590
and that's physical
force having to be used

00:21:05.590 --> 00:21:08.910
by police officers on a
person with a developmental

00:21:08.910 --> 00:21:10.720
or intellectual disability.

00:21:10.720 --> 00:21:13.480
And we know that when,
many times when police

00:21:13.480 --> 00:21:16.290
are called to incidents involving a person

00:21:16.290 --> 00:21:19.490
with an intellectual or
developmental disability,

00:21:19.490 --> 00:21:22.333
because of a perceived threat or concern,

00:21:23.240 --> 00:21:26.380
due to the oftentimes,
the disability itself,

00:21:26.380 --> 00:21:29.240
is really difficult to distinguish.

00:21:29.240 --> 00:21:31.870
Like I said, some people,
there's no outwardly signs

00:21:31.870 --> 00:21:34.550
of any type of disability.

00:21:34.550 --> 00:21:37.554
And those are much more
difficult to deal with

00:21:37.554 --> 00:21:40.188
from a policing perspective.

00:21:40.188 --> 00:21:43.700
And whether this call for
service is self-initiated,

00:21:43.700 --> 00:21:46.870
or whether officers are
responding to a dispatch call

00:21:46.870 --> 00:21:50.380
for service, our training needs to focus

00:21:50.380 --> 00:21:52.200
on slowing things down.

00:21:52.200 --> 00:21:55.150
There's a saying that I
learned early on in policing

00:21:55.150 --> 00:21:58.260
in my career: time is on your side.

00:21:58.260 --> 00:22:01.900
If you can slow things down,
you're gonna be better off.

00:22:01.900 --> 00:22:04.100
And that's a learned skill,

00:22:04.100 --> 00:22:05.450
because when you're in
the heat of the moment,

00:22:05.450 --> 00:22:08.360
and you roll up on a call, and it's chaos,

00:22:08.360 --> 00:22:11.550
oftentimes, you react based
on what your training is,

00:22:11.550 --> 00:22:13.810
what your experience is,
but sometimes you have to

00:22:13.810 --> 00:22:16.693
kind of collect yourself, and
you have to slow things down.

00:22:17.590 --> 00:22:19.656
That is the mode of training that is

00:22:19.656 --> 00:22:21.470
on the forefront of law enforcement.

00:22:21.470 --> 00:22:24.740
As simple as it sounds, and
as basic as this sounds,

00:22:24.740 --> 00:22:25.843
easier said than done.

00:22:26.720 --> 00:22:29.093
Slowing things down,
create time and distance.

00:22:31.110 --> 00:22:33.720
Understanding the
possibility that a disability

00:22:33.720 --> 00:22:36.580
may be a contributing factor is key,

00:22:36.580 --> 00:22:39.530
and responding accordingly
to the overall situation,

00:22:39.530 --> 00:22:43.593
not the initial perception, is also key.

00:22:47.180 --> 00:22:50.480
A little bit, statistically speaking,

00:22:50.480 --> 00:22:51.760
about police use of force.

00:22:51.760 --> 00:22:53.720
Now, the chart that
you see in front of you

00:22:53.720 --> 00:22:58.100
kind of breaks down, research
shows that approximately 25%,

00:22:58.100 --> 00:23:02.140
some say as high as 50%,
of persons killed by police

00:23:02.140 --> 00:23:05.270
may have a mental disorder,
or that person was

00:23:05.270 --> 00:23:07.510
in a mental health crisis,
including under the influence

00:23:07.510 --> 00:23:10.880
of a controlled substance
during this encounter.

00:23:10.880 --> 00:23:12.590
Now, what I believe, as a professional,

00:23:12.590 --> 00:23:14.520
as a chief of police sitting
here in front of you,

00:23:14.520 --> 00:23:18.100
that hidden in those
numbers are a lot of people

00:23:18.100 --> 00:23:20.680
with developmental disabilities.

00:23:20.680 --> 00:23:24.500
And with over 18,000 police departments

00:23:24.500 --> 00:23:27.451
across the country, and really
no national standardization

00:23:27.451 --> 00:23:31.040
of what has to be tracked
and needs to be tracked,

00:23:31.040 --> 00:23:32.900
we don't really know what that number is,

00:23:32.900 --> 00:23:34.570
to be quite frank with you.

00:23:34.570 --> 00:23:37.856
And it is my hope that before
I leave this profession

00:23:37.856 --> 00:23:42.630
that we do a better job,
because with anything,

00:23:42.630 --> 00:23:44.570
when you have data and research,

00:23:44.570 --> 00:23:45.910
then you can start figuring out

00:23:45.910 --> 00:23:47.770
what you need to do to make things better.

00:23:47.770 --> 00:23:50.143
We just don't have the
data on this subject.

00:23:52.380 --> 00:23:55.270
Incidents involving
individuals with disabilities

00:23:55.270 --> 00:23:57.065
and developmental or intellectual,

00:23:57.065 --> 00:23:59.520
they go under the radar,
to be quite frank with you,

00:23:59.520 --> 00:24:01.863
because we're not really capturing it.

00:24:11.550 --> 00:24:12.400
Sorry about that.

00:24:13.860 --> 00:24:17.323
I skipped ahead too
far, give me one...okay.

00:24:18.740 --> 00:24:21.763
Here are more statistics,

00:24:23.500 --> 00:24:25.940
and basically, what this graph shows

00:24:25.940 --> 00:24:28.980
is as the number of calls
for service involving

00:24:28.980 --> 00:24:32.160
persons in crisis increase,
law enforcement reexamine

00:24:32.160 --> 00:24:35.070
the basic training philosophies

00:24:35.070 --> 00:24:38.390
and standard operating procedures
to adjust our response,

00:24:38.390 --> 00:24:40.317
the officers' response to incidents

00:24:40.317 --> 00:24:42.423
involving a person in crisis.

00:24:44.240 --> 00:24:47.870
And the whole spirit behind that was

00:24:47.870 --> 00:24:51.030
we wanna minimize getting to a situation

00:24:51.030 --> 00:24:53.360
where we have to use force,

00:24:53.360 --> 00:24:55.170
oftentimes when force can be prevented

00:24:55.170 --> 00:24:59.253
if we know what the situation
is that we're facing.

00:25:02.250 --> 00:25:05.490
The San Francisco Police
Department in 2015,

00:25:05.490 --> 00:25:08.760
we really kind of stepped
up our game and expanded

00:25:08.760 --> 00:25:13.533
our effort, including our
crisis intervention training,

00:25:14.430 --> 00:25:17.270
to better understand how to
deal with persons in crisis.

00:25:17.270 --> 00:25:21.950
Now this doesn't specifically
speak with the intellectual

00:25:21.950 --> 00:25:24.193
and developmental disabilities training,

00:25:26.049 --> 00:25:28.800
but just better training on how to deal

00:25:28.800 --> 00:25:31.800
with a person in crisis was a good step

00:25:31.800 --> 00:25:32.870
in the right direction for us,

00:25:32.870 --> 00:25:37.500
because in that, now we are
specifically focusing more

00:25:37.500 --> 00:25:40.060
on the other side of it, you know,

00:25:40.060 --> 00:25:43.070
how much of this is due to developmental

00:25:43.070 --> 00:25:45.110
or intellectual disabilities?

00:25:45.110 --> 00:25:47.500
You know, the changes that were included.

00:25:47.500 --> 00:25:49.010
Slowing things down, you're gonna hear me

00:25:49.010 --> 00:25:50.270
say that over and over again.

00:25:50.270 --> 00:25:52.350
Creating time and distance.

00:25:52.350 --> 00:25:54.870
If you have to use force,
use a proportional amount

00:25:54.870 --> 00:25:57.603
of force, an amount of
force that's reasonable.

00:25:58.900 --> 00:26:01.920
Increasing our training techniques

00:26:01.920 --> 00:26:04.706
to reinforce de-escalation.

00:26:04.706 --> 00:26:09.360
And basically limiting
force against people

00:26:09.360 --> 00:26:11.723
that are only a danger to themselves.

00:26:12.660 --> 00:26:17.660
Also, tools of the trade, we
have new tools of the trade,

00:26:18.206 --> 00:26:21.740
extended range impact weapons

00:26:21.740 --> 00:26:24.730
where we don't have to
necessarily use lethal force

00:26:24.730 --> 00:26:26.900
when we do get beyond a situation

00:26:26.900 --> 00:26:28.050
that can be handled through

00:26:28.050 --> 00:26:31.330
de-escalation or verbal techniques.

00:26:31.330 --> 00:26:33.360
What can we do short of lethal force?

00:26:33.360 --> 00:26:35.810
So all these things I think have helped us

00:26:35.810 --> 00:26:37.403
really reduce our use of force,

00:26:38.383 --> 00:26:40.720
and since 2015, our use
of force in San Francisco

00:26:40.720 --> 00:26:43.033
is down about 27% overall.

00:26:44.140 --> 00:26:46.910
But again, we have to do
better in really calling out

00:26:49.610 --> 00:26:51.824
the developmental disability issues,

00:26:51.824 --> 00:26:52.657
because we really don't know what

00:26:52.657 --> 00:26:54.630
that number is, to be
quite frank with you.

00:27:01.840 --> 00:27:03.600
So when an incident involves a person

00:27:03.600 --> 00:27:06.100
with an intellectual or
developmental disability

00:27:06.100 --> 00:27:08.240
that at times may present characteristics

00:27:08.240 --> 00:27:10.050
that are considered aggressive, violent,

00:27:10.050 --> 00:27:13.450
such as with certain types of conditions

00:27:13.450 --> 00:27:16.407
like Asperger's, and you
know, the mere presence

00:27:16.407 --> 00:27:18.275
of a a police officer in uniform

00:27:18.275 --> 00:27:21.853
may trigger an unwanted response.

