00:29:54.920 --> 00:29:57.973
Again, the therapist is there to help.

00:29:58.910 --> 00:30:03.910
Now, I will say this,
I don't wanna get into

00:30:04.320 --> 00:30:07.590
right or wrong or what
happened on that shooting,

00:30:07.590 --> 00:30:09.570
but what I do know about this is

00:30:10.413 --> 00:30:13.490
slowing things down, listening.

00:30:13.490 --> 00:30:16.680
You know, the therapist, I
think you saw in the video,

00:30:16.680 --> 00:30:18.990
he was pointing out that
what was in the man's hand

00:30:18.990 --> 00:30:21.000
was a toy truck, actually.

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:25.320
And the officers never
processed that information,

00:30:25.320 --> 00:30:28.350
apparently, and they felt that a life

00:30:28.350 --> 00:30:31.160
was being threatened, and
it resulted in tragedy.

00:30:31.160 --> 00:30:34.570
Now, Mr. Kinsey was the one
that was ultimately shot

00:30:34.570 --> 00:30:36.610
by the police, and he
survived his injuries,

00:30:36.610 --> 00:30:40.380
but again, understanding, you know,

00:30:40.380 --> 00:30:43.530
I don't know that the officers really knew

00:30:43.530 --> 00:30:45.803
what they had in front of them.

00:30:45.803 --> 00:30:48.460
And this is why understanding
is vitally important

00:30:48.460 --> 00:30:50.823
for us to not have this happen.

00:30:54.400 --> 00:30:56.350
It's a tragedy, and we have to get better.

00:30:56.350 --> 00:30:58.060
We have to learn from
these types of incidents

00:30:58.060 --> 00:31:01.240
to get better, to be better at what we do.

00:31:01.240 --> 00:31:02.120
So how do we do that?

00:31:02.120 --> 00:31:04.370
How do we realize changes?

00:31:04.370 --> 00:31:07.150
Now, as I talked about, you know,

00:31:07.150 --> 00:31:09.948
when I put on my father hat,

00:31:09.948 --> 00:31:12.670
and having a child with a developmental

00:31:12.670 --> 00:31:16.190
and intellectual disability,
I think about this.

00:31:16.190 --> 00:31:17.490
I think about it often.

00:31:17.490 --> 00:31:21.260
I, what's gonna happen, I
can't be there all the time.

00:31:21.260 --> 00:31:23.060
My wife can't be there all the time.

00:31:24.710 --> 00:31:25.860
But we can make a difference,

00:31:25.860 --> 00:31:28.290
we in law enforcement, people
like me and Captain Moore

00:31:28.290 --> 00:31:30.860
and others, many others,
we can make a difference,

00:31:30.860 --> 00:31:32.700
to make sure we have
the best understanding

00:31:32.700 --> 00:31:36.810
that if we encounter, that
we do the best job we can

00:31:36.810 --> 00:31:39.163
to try not to have a tragedy occur.

00:31:43.370 --> 00:31:45.593
And those encounters happen daily.

00:31:46.890 --> 00:31:49.368
They happen in many ways, casual,

00:31:49.368 --> 00:31:51.473
people asking for directions,

00:31:52.610 --> 00:31:55.340
public event or just
walking down the street,

00:31:55.340 --> 00:31:58.226
people being a victim
or witness of a crime,

00:31:58.226 --> 00:32:01.940
people being suspects, person of interest.

00:32:01.940 --> 00:32:03.180
And it's not to say that people

00:32:03.180 --> 00:32:05.770
with developmental
disabilities don't get involved

00:32:05.770 --> 00:32:08.891
in criminal activity, because
sometimes that does happen,

00:32:08.891 --> 00:32:11.350
and that's another side of this story

00:32:11.350 --> 00:32:12.900
that we have to be better at,

00:32:12.900 --> 00:32:15.050
really understanding
how to deal with that.

00:32:16.430 --> 00:32:19.860
And a person being the
subject of an encounter,

00:32:19.860 --> 00:32:24.500
when that call is
dispatched by a bystander

00:32:24.500 --> 00:32:26.040
that is seeing something that they believe

00:32:26.040 --> 00:32:30.380
is criminal activity
or suspicious activity,

00:32:30.380 --> 00:32:32.120
and we get dispatched
to calls all the time,

00:32:32.120 --> 00:32:33.820
and we're gonna talk a little bit about

00:32:33.820 --> 00:32:36.220
some of the issues concerning that,

00:32:36.220 --> 00:32:38.420
particularly when it
comes to implicit bias.

00:32:48.940 --> 00:32:51.880
This is a vulnerable
population, as I said before,

00:32:51.880 --> 00:32:54.080
and you can see on the chart before you,

00:32:54.080 --> 00:32:55.840
the information gathered, this came from

00:32:55.840 --> 00:32:58.020
the United States Bureau of Justice.

00:32:58.020 --> 00:33:00.830
It indicates that between 2011 and 2015,

00:33:00.830 --> 00:33:02.300
the rate of violent victimization

00:33:02.300 --> 00:33:06.270
against persons with disability
was two and one half times

00:33:06.270 --> 00:33:11.253
higher than it was for
persons without disabilities.

00:33:12.410 --> 00:33:15.480
Persons between age of 12
and 15 had the highest rate

00:33:15.480 --> 00:33:18.853
of victimization than any other age group.

00:33:20.090 --> 00:33:21.593
It's a vulnerable population,

00:33:22.640 --> 00:33:24.600
which is why we have to be on top of this,

00:33:24.600 --> 00:33:28.080
we who come in contact with
the victims and the witnesses,

00:33:28.080 --> 00:33:29.713
we have to be on top of this.

00:33:30.750 --> 00:33:32.560
In terms of encounters
with law enforcement,

00:33:32.560 --> 00:33:35.600
we also know that persons
with intellectual,

00:33:35.600 --> 00:33:40.600
intellectual disabilities
may be more easily targeted

00:33:43.773 --> 00:33:46.650
for victimization because
they are vulnerable.

00:33:46.650 --> 00:33:48.630
People can be manipulated,

00:33:48.630 --> 00:33:52.538
and they are less likely or
able to report victimization,

00:33:52.538 --> 00:33:54.810
because the perpetrator is a friend.

00:33:54.810 --> 00:33:56.353
Now that is a big problem.

00:33:57.800 --> 00:34:02.040
A lot of people, because
they do feel isolated,

00:34:02.040 --> 00:34:05.050
or feel like they don't have friends,

00:34:05.050 --> 00:34:08.710
are really over-reaching to find a friend.

00:34:08.710 --> 00:34:11.630
And sometimes that's taken advantage of.

00:34:11.630 --> 00:34:14.150
As a parent, I worry
about that all the time.

00:34:14.150 --> 00:34:17.270
People just wanna be,
feel like anybody else,

00:34:17.270 --> 00:34:20.270
want a friend, want somebody
that I can talk to and rely on,

00:34:20.270 --> 00:34:23.070
and there are people out
there that prey on that,

00:34:23.070 --> 00:34:24.626
and it's a problem for us,

00:34:24.626 --> 00:34:26.400
and it's a problem for
us in law enforcement,

00:34:26.400 --> 00:34:28.220
and it's a problem for us as parents,

00:34:28.220 --> 00:34:32.790
because it's something that
sometimes you just can't,

00:34:32.790 --> 00:34:35.110
as much as you talk to your child,

00:34:35.110 --> 00:34:37.400
or as law enforcement,
as much as we train,

00:34:37.400 --> 00:34:40.317
we can't control people
who wanna prey upon

00:34:40.317 --> 00:34:43.230
a vulnerable population,
so it's something that

00:34:43.230 --> 00:34:45.980
we have to deal with in law
enforcement and as parents.

00:34:50.310 --> 00:34:54.230
So we're gonna go into a
little bit about subjects

00:34:56.500 --> 00:35:00.300
or people that are determined
to be persons of interest.

00:35:00.300 --> 00:35:03.730
Now, this next slide, it'll
be probably a little bit

00:35:03.730 --> 00:35:06.450
surprising to some of you, and some of you

00:35:06.450 --> 00:35:08.210
probably already know this.

00:35:08.210 --> 00:35:10.760
Incarceration of Americans
with disabilities,

00:35:10.760 --> 00:35:15.760
now this also came from the
Bureau of Justice statistics,

00:35:17.200 --> 00:35:19.150
and if you look at the slides,

00:35:19.150 --> 00:35:21.800
very, very high percentages of people

00:35:21.800 --> 00:35:25.323
who are incarcerated have disabilities.

00:35:26.860 --> 00:35:29.823
That is very alarming for many reasons.

00:35:31.650 --> 00:35:34.460
But it illustrates why it's so important

00:35:34.460 --> 00:35:38.680
for us police officers
to train, to understand,

00:35:38.680 --> 00:35:42.540
and maybe to turn these numbers
in a different direction.

00:35:42.540 --> 00:35:44.533
But that is a very alarming statistic.

00:35:45.730 --> 00:35:49.340
Studies show that people
with developmental

00:35:49.340 --> 00:35:51.390
and intellectual disabilities
are overrepresented

00:35:51.390 --> 00:35:52.840
in the criminal justice system.

00:35:52.840 --> 00:35:54.840
They represent two to three percent

00:35:54.840 --> 00:35:56.190
of the general population,

00:35:56.190 --> 00:36:00.003
and four to 10 percent of
incarcerated persons overall.

00:36:00.876 --> 00:36:03.680
What that means to us is
during a normal shift,

00:36:03.680 --> 00:36:05.120
we're likely to come across somebody

00:36:05.120 --> 00:36:07.710
with an intellectual or a
developmental disability.

00:36:07.710 --> 00:36:10.620
Sometimes we can ferret that
out based on our training,

00:36:10.620 --> 00:36:11.653
sometimes we can't.

00:36:20.450 --> 00:36:23.570
So when we're taking or
encountering a person

00:36:23.570 --> 00:36:26.120
with disabilities,
intellectual or developmental,

00:36:26.120 --> 00:36:29.350
into custody, we have
to give particular care

00:36:29.350 --> 00:36:31.260
to the manner in which
the person is placed

00:36:31.260 --> 00:36:34.133
in physical custody if those
disabilities are physical,

00:36:36.270 --> 00:36:39.900
because if we don't, it
can elicit a response

00:36:39.900 --> 00:36:44.780
that can be unpredictable
and, quite frankly, unwanted.

00:36:44.780 --> 00:36:48.893
The issue here is that
sometimes the person

00:36:48.893 --> 00:36:53.410
cannot articulate what
those disabilities are.

00:36:53.410 --> 00:36:57.223
And when I talk about slowing
down and taking extra time,

00:36:57.223 --> 00:37:00.630
it's really important
for us, when we really,

00:37:00.630 --> 00:37:02.960
at the time we determine
that we're dealing

00:37:02.960 --> 00:37:04.500
with somebody with an intellectual

00:37:04.500 --> 00:37:07.550
or a developmental
disability, you really do have

00:37:07.550 --> 00:37:09.000
to spend extra time.

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:09.863
You really do.

00:37:11.122 --> 00:37:16.122
My son has some
developmental malformities,

00:37:17.050 --> 00:37:19.290
not so sure that he would
be able to articulate that

00:37:19.290 --> 00:37:21.090
if an officer were to
place him in handcuffs,

00:37:21.090 --> 00:37:23.016
to be quite frank with you.

00:37:23.016 --> 00:37:26.200
And if he doesn't, it
could be harmful to him.

00:37:26.200 --> 00:37:27.740
So we know that's an issue.

00:37:27.740 --> 00:37:29.810
And it goes back to understanding,

00:37:29.810 --> 00:37:32.160
and you're gonna see another
training video in a second,

00:37:32.160 --> 00:37:35.860
in a few minutes,
rather, about recognition

00:37:35.860 --> 00:37:38.850
and understanding, because
we have to spend extra time

00:37:38.850 --> 00:37:42.510
to get the information that
we need in order for us

00:37:42.510 --> 00:37:47.110
to do the right job and a good job.

00:37:47.110 --> 00:37:49.630
So that takes communication,
it takes patience,

00:37:49.630 --> 00:37:51.130
and it really takes understanding

00:37:51.130 --> 00:37:53.630
and being able to recognize
what we're looking at.

00:37:57.790 --> 00:38:00.210
Now, here's another snippet, as I said,

00:38:00.210 --> 00:38:02.450
of a training video
that'll help us get better

00:38:02.450 --> 00:38:03.950
at our encounters with individuals

00:38:03.950 --> 00:38:06.710
with intellectual or
developmental disabilities.

00:38:06.710 --> 00:38:08.360
John, if you could play this one.

00:38:10.020 --> 00:38:11.700
- You could be helping them,

00:38:11.700 --> 00:38:13.736
they could've been missing for days,

00:38:13.736 --> 00:38:17.300
they could've just come out of
a really dangerous situation,

00:38:17.300 --> 00:38:20.410
and they're unaware that
you're trying to help them.

00:38:20.410 --> 00:38:24.890
Try not to look like
you're corralling them,

00:38:24.890 --> 00:38:28.500
but do that in a stealth-like way

00:38:28.500 --> 00:38:30.310
so you can cut off the running route.

00:38:30.310 --> 00:38:33.000
'Cause they wanna get
back to their comfort zone

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:34.820
for the moment, and it's, momentarily,

00:38:34.820 --> 00:38:36.520
that's all they're thinking about.

00:38:37.540 --> 00:38:40.419
Be very careful as first responders,

00:38:40.419 --> 00:38:44.631
we know that the person affected by autism

00:38:44.631 --> 00:38:49.171
is either in a combative
state, a highly anxious mode,

00:38:49.171 --> 00:38:53.150
motivated by seeking their comfort zone.

00:38:53.150 --> 00:38:55.500
So they are doing everything they can

00:38:55.500 --> 00:38:57.763
to get away from us and the stimulus.

00:38:59.070 --> 00:39:01.960
Kill the lights in the
car, kill the siren,

00:39:01.960 --> 00:39:05.810
maybe lower the radios, and
maybe find the calmest person

00:39:05.810 --> 00:39:09.343
within your responding
group to do the talking.

00:39:10.340 --> 00:39:14.150
Loud noises, loud voices, commanding talk

00:39:14.150 --> 00:39:16.490
is something they're gonna shy away from.

00:39:16.490 --> 00:39:19.693
You'll get better results
with a calmer voice.

00:39:21.210 --> 00:39:24.000
- Now, as you saw, Officer Padilla has a,

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:26.875
he's the father of a child with autism.

00:39:26.875 --> 00:39:31.030
Like me, many of us who live this,

00:39:31.030 --> 00:39:33.460
have a better understanding,
so one thing about

00:39:33.460 --> 00:39:35.949
this profession, the police profession,

00:39:35.949 --> 00:39:40.180
there's no better trainer, if
you wanna illustrate a point,

00:39:40.180 --> 00:39:41.610
than another police officer,

00:39:41.610 --> 00:39:43.150
'cause cops tend to listen to other cops.

00:39:43.150 --> 00:39:46.446
So to have people, ah, it's true.

00:39:46.446 --> 00:39:47.950
(audience laughs)

00:39:47.950 --> 00:39:50.760
But to have, you know,
an officer like Padilla,

00:39:50.760 --> 00:39:54.050
or even some of the other
people in our department,

00:39:54.050 --> 00:39:56.850
officers in our department,
sworn and civilian,

00:39:56.850 --> 00:40:00.700
who can really take their life experiences

00:40:00.700 --> 00:40:04.680
and translate that in a
relatable way to training

00:40:04.680 --> 00:40:06.740
is really, really important.

00:40:06.740 --> 00:40:09.880
This video was really well
received by our force,

00:40:09.880 --> 00:40:12.360
and these are the type things that we have

00:40:12.360 --> 00:40:14.070
to continue to do to get better.

00:40:14.070 --> 00:40:16.132
'Cause it's all about understanding.

00:40:16.132 --> 00:40:17.660
You know, I talked about caregivers.

00:40:17.660 --> 00:40:21.450
I perfectly understand
that, if I'm dealing with

00:40:21.450 --> 00:40:24.810
a person with disabilities,
sometimes I might not need

00:40:24.810 --> 00:40:25.950
to be talking to that person.

00:40:25.950 --> 00:40:28.440
I might need to be talking to the person,

00:40:28.440 --> 00:40:30.483
the caregiver, or the person, the aide

00:40:30.483 --> 00:40:31.960
who can better articulate,

00:40:31.960 --> 00:40:34.296
who has a better understanding of

00:40:34.296 --> 00:40:37.681
what the disabilities are
and can articulate to me

00:40:37.681 --> 00:40:39.840
what I need to know to do my job.

00:40:39.840 --> 00:40:43.050
So having officers like
Padilla on the police force

00:40:43.050 --> 00:40:44.220
really are helpful.

00:40:44.220 --> 00:40:46.550
Having people like Captain Moore

00:40:46.550 --> 00:40:48.950
really are helpful to get that message

00:40:48.950 --> 00:40:50.640
across to the other
officers who don't have

00:40:50.640 --> 00:40:51.840
those personal experiences,

00:40:51.840 --> 00:40:54.560
so it's a really, really important
piece of training for us.

00:40:54.560 --> 00:40:57.713
And I'm really proud that we're
taking the steps to do this.

00:41:01.400 --> 00:41:05.100
Interviews with suspects
or persons of interest,

00:41:05.100 --> 00:41:10.100
now, I was, in my prior years,

00:41:10.140 --> 00:41:12.460
a homicide detective for a few years.

00:41:12.460 --> 00:41:14.954
Also, I spent a couple years investigating

00:41:14.954 --> 00:41:19.030
gang-related, mainly violent crime.

00:41:19.030 --> 00:41:22.977
One of the things that I saw, often,

00:41:22.977 --> 00:41:27.560
was a lot of the people
that I came in contact with

00:41:27.560 --> 00:41:29.380
in my mind, and I'm not a psychologist,

00:41:29.380 --> 00:41:34.130
but I truly believe that there
were disabilities present

00:41:35.400 --> 00:41:37.590
that had never been diagnosed.

00:41:37.590 --> 00:41:40.380
And the reason that's so important,

00:41:40.380 --> 00:41:42.950
in terms of from both a legal perspective

00:41:42.950 --> 00:41:45.690
and as an investigator, you
really have to get a sense

00:41:45.690 --> 00:41:46.523
of what you're dealing with,

00:41:46.523 --> 00:41:51.523
because if you don't, it
can lead to some places

00:41:52.010 --> 00:41:53.110
that you don't wanna go,

00:41:53.110 --> 00:41:55.350
false confessions, fake confessions.

00:41:55.350 --> 00:41:56.550
People wanna please.

00:41:56.550 --> 00:41:59.070
A lot of times the
individuals with disabilities,

00:41:59.070 --> 00:42:02.960
intellectual and developmental,
they wanna please,

00:42:02.960 --> 00:42:06.447
and if you don't recognize that,

00:42:06.447 --> 00:42:08.890
you can get a false confession.

00:42:08.890 --> 00:42:10.930
So it's really, really
important, it's really,

00:42:10.930 --> 00:42:13.979
really important that that
recognition takes place.

00:42:13.979 --> 00:42:16.670
Feeling overwhelmed by police presence,

00:42:16.670 --> 00:42:19.230
knowing how far to push,

00:42:19.230 --> 00:42:21.050
not understanding
instructions or commands,

00:42:21.050 --> 00:42:22.760
saying things that they
believe police wanna hear,

00:42:22.760 --> 00:42:26.270
all these things can be mitigated

00:42:26.270 --> 00:42:28.570
with proper training and
better understanding.

00:42:33.860 --> 00:42:37.121
Now, when those encounters
are self-initiated

00:42:37.121 --> 00:42:41.494
by the police officer,
oftentimes, it's because of

00:42:41.494 --> 00:42:46.130
what we call either a reasonable suspicion

00:42:46.130 --> 00:42:48.640
or sometimes probable cause

00:42:48.640 --> 00:42:50.800
that some crime has been committed.

00:42:50.800 --> 00:42:55.180
And, oftentimes, though,
the calls are relayed

00:42:55.180 --> 00:42:58.130
from people in the public, the dispatch.

00:42:58.130 --> 00:43:00.530
Now, we've all seen calls,
particularly lately,

00:43:00.530 --> 00:43:03.360
with people that called
in on an individual

00:43:03.360 --> 00:43:05.530
thinking one thing, and
some of them have been

00:43:05.530 --> 00:43:07.415
a little bit over the top in terms of

00:43:07.415 --> 00:43:12.415
what I think to be implicit biases.

00:43:13.230 --> 00:43:16.060
And when we respond to these calls,

00:43:16.060 --> 00:43:21.060
we really have to be able
to make our own assessment.

00:43:22.590 --> 00:43:24.680
It is important what the
caller is seeing and saying

00:43:24.680 --> 00:43:27.492
and all that, but we have to be prepared

00:43:27.492 --> 00:43:30.655
and have our officers
have the skills needed

00:43:30.655 --> 00:43:34.900
to both respond safely
and to really ferret out

00:43:34.900 --> 00:43:38.980
fact from fiction, bias from reality,

00:43:38.980 --> 00:43:43.080
and in terms of the
special needs population,

00:43:43.080 --> 00:43:44.830
I think that's even more important,

00:43:44.830 --> 00:43:47.640
because there are a lot of implicit biases

00:43:47.640 --> 00:43:51.063
when it comes to special
needs individuals.

00:43:56.110 --> 00:43:58.360
Bias by proxy is what I'm talking about.

00:43:58.360 --> 00:44:01.100
So I call the police,
and I see an individual

00:44:01.100 --> 00:44:04.134
that I think is doing something
suspicious or whatever,

00:44:04.134 --> 00:44:06.123
what's shaping my perception?

00:44:07.110 --> 00:44:09.080
How much have I been trained on this?

00:44:09.080 --> 00:44:11.850
If I see somebody that has Down syndrome

00:44:11.850 --> 00:44:13.630
and they're wobbling, and
I think they're either

00:44:13.630 --> 00:44:17.328
under the influence or
mentally impaired or whatever,

00:44:17.328 --> 00:44:20.900
am I taking the extra
time to really understand

00:44:20.900 --> 00:44:22.750
what it is that I'm seeing

00:44:22.750 --> 00:44:25.960
before I call dispatch to have an officer.

00:44:25.960 --> 00:44:27.900
Oftentimes, I will tell you, people don't.

00:44:27.900 --> 00:44:30.670
They call, and we get there.

00:44:30.670 --> 00:44:33.570
So it's really incumbent
upon us to be able

00:44:33.570 --> 00:44:35.600
to filter through all that.

00:44:35.600 --> 00:44:37.570
And according to the Vera Institute,

00:44:37.570 --> 00:44:40.530
bias by proxy poses a major challenge

00:44:40.530 --> 00:44:42.720
to officers responding to calls.

00:44:42.720 --> 00:44:47.310
And this was a 2008
opinion, so it's a little

00:44:47.310 --> 00:44:49.590
over 10 years old, but Dale Larson,

00:44:49.590 --> 00:44:53.175
who was a professor at
the UCLA School of Law,

00:44:53.175 --> 00:44:58.175
he made it his mission
to support expanding

00:44:58.930 --> 00:45:00.823
federal protections for individuals

00:45:00.823 --> 00:45:02.830
with developmental disabilities.

00:45:02.830 --> 00:45:05.650
He felt that implicit bias
with people with disabilities

00:45:05.650 --> 00:45:07.762
is one of the strongest
types of implicit bias

00:45:07.762 --> 00:45:11.550
in our society, he felt
that strongly about it.

00:45:11.550 --> 00:45:16.020
And it does play a role in how we respond.

00:45:16.020 --> 00:45:19.730
We respond to what is on
the screen in front of us,

00:45:19.730 --> 00:45:23.650
and oftentimes, if that
body of information

00:45:23.650 --> 00:45:24.850
that's on the screen in front of us

00:45:24.850 --> 00:45:27.170
is driven by implicit bias, it may impact

00:45:27.170 --> 00:45:28.310
the way that we respond to things.

00:45:28.310 --> 00:45:30.954
So we have to be able to discern.

00:45:30.954 --> 00:45:33.240
I'll go back to what I said earlier.

00:45:33.240 --> 00:45:36.130
We, as police officers,
have to be able to discern.

