00:48:20.717 --> 00:48:23.134
- All right, three Adam 13...

00:48:24.857 --> 00:48:26.320
- The role of the police officer

00:48:26.320 --> 00:48:28.980
is one of the most complicated in society.

00:48:28.980 --> 00:48:30.720
You're asked to respond to numerous calls

00:48:30.720 --> 00:48:32.970
on a daily basis and make effective

00:48:32.970 --> 00:48:36.370
and ethical decisions using
your training and experience.

00:48:36.370 --> 00:48:38.780
Consider the scene we just witnessed.

00:48:38.780 --> 00:48:41.470
How many calls for service
have you responded to

00:48:41.470 --> 00:48:44.310
which begin almost exactly like this?

00:48:44.310 --> 00:48:47.350
How much do you really know walking in?

00:48:47.350 --> 00:48:49.215
Sometimes the most important
piece of information

00:48:49.215 --> 00:48:51.860
is the one you don't have access to.

00:48:51.860 --> 00:48:54.690
Autism spectrum disorder
is extremely common,

00:48:54.690 --> 00:48:56.310
but it might not always be clear

00:48:56.310 --> 00:48:58.120
when you're encountering it.

00:48:58.120 --> 00:49:00.373
You police a large and diverse community.

00:49:01.280 --> 00:49:04.010
As police officers, you
have a duty to treat

00:49:04.010 --> 00:49:06.620
all members of the community with respect,

00:49:06.620 --> 00:49:10.120
provide trust, be neutral
in your encounters,

00:49:10.120 --> 00:49:12.770
and provide every person a voice.

00:49:12.770 --> 00:49:15.086
In the next few minutes
we will discuss autism,

00:49:15.086 --> 00:49:18.140
how this condition manifests itself,

00:49:18.140 --> 00:49:20.420
and the ways that police
officers can safely

00:49:20.420 --> 00:49:23.513
and effectively serve these
members of our community.

00:49:25.170 --> 00:49:27.430
- So again, this is just
a portion of the video

00:49:27.430 --> 00:49:29.610
that we give our officers so they have

00:49:29.610 --> 00:49:34.333
a better understanding of how
to respond, how to encounter.

00:49:38.710 --> 00:49:41.400
I'm gonna do a public safety
announcement plug here,

00:49:41.400 --> 00:49:45.385
so for those of you that,
and many people in this room

00:49:45.385 --> 00:49:50.050
probably are more educated
than the average individual

00:49:50.050 --> 00:49:53.550
on really understanding what you're seeing

00:49:53.550 --> 00:49:54.750
in terms of dealing with a person

00:49:54.750 --> 00:49:57.410
with an intellectual or
developmental disability.

00:49:57.410 --> 00:50:00.410
What I would ask, from a
public service perspective,

00:50:00.410 --> 00:50:05.050
is as much as you have
conversations with your friends,

00:50:05.050 --> 00:50:08.530
neighbors, loved ones, is
to have those conversations.

00:50:08.530 --> 00:50:12.080
Help educate, because bias
by proxy is a problem for us.

00:50:12.080 --> 00:50:13.290
I can tell you that.

00:50:13.290 --> 00:50:15.767
People call on what they
believe is happening,

00:50:15.767 --> 00:50:17.690
and we have to respond to it.

00:50:17.690 --> 00:50:22.690
And as much as we train and
try to provide the tools

00:50:22.890 --> 00:50:24.620
for our officers to recognize what it is

00:50:24.620 --> 00:50:27.330
that they're dealing with,
we still get the calls.

00:50:27.330 --> 00:50:30.230
There is a need for
educating the general public

00:50:30.230 --> 00:50:33.253
to take the time and try
to determine what you got

00:50:33.253 --> 00:50:34.920
before you make the call.

00:50:34.920 --> 00:50:38.950
So what I ask of the audience
is have those conversations.

00:50:38.950 --> 00:50:40.700
Please continue to have
those conversations.

00:50:40.700 --> 00:50:44.245
Many of you are educators,
many of you work in this world,

00:50:44.245 --> 00:50:49.245
it's a message that needs to be spread

00:50:50.090 --> 00:50:53.670
in terms of implicit bias,

00:50:53.670 --> 00:50:56.520
taking the time to recognize
what you're looking at,

00:50:56.520 --> 00:51:00.810
so you don't make a bad situation
worse by your own biases.

00:51:00.810 --> 00:51:02.700
And that's something that I think,

00:51:02.700 --> 00:51:04.550
as a society, we gotta get better at.

00:51:13.180 --> 00:51:16.260
What all this is about
for us is we wanna prepare

00:51:16.260 --> 00:51:19.820
our officers to prevent
the need to use force,

00:51:19.820 --> 00:51:23.830
not to react to these types
of situations by using force.

00:51:23.830 --> 00:51:26.777
That training video that Officer Padilla

00:51:26.777 --> 00:51:31.340
and Officer Bannity, with
the gentleman with autism,

00:51:31.340 --> 00:51:33.350
those situations often go sideways

00:51:33.350 --> 00:51:35.130
just because there's no awareness

00:51:35.130 --> 00:51:37.130
of what is in front of you.

00:51:37.130 --> 00:51:40.563
There's no awareness that
the person has autism

00:51:42.630 --> 00:51:44.900
or whatever the issue is,

00:51:44.900 --> 00:51:49.900
and without awareness,
you have more probability

00:51:51.170 --> 00:51:52.470
of things going sideways.

00:51:52.470 --> 00:51:56.020
So the training is definitely
needed and necessary,

00:51:56.020 --> 00:51:56.853
and that's why we do it.

00:51:56.853 --> 00:51:59.610
We wanna prevent these
situations form escalating

00:51:59.610 --> 00:52:04.210
to a point where they get to a situation

00:52:04.210 --> 00:52:07.623
where force has to be used
to get it back under control.

00:52:09.230 --> 00:52:13.570
According to a report
by the Police Executive

00:52:13.570 --> 00:52:16.325
Research Forum, better known as PERF,

00:52:16.325 --> 00:52:19.300
nearly all the use of force incidents

00:52:19.300 --> 00:52:20.940
that have proven to be controversial,

00:52:20.940 --> 00:52:23.830
and this study was over a number of years,

00:52:23.830 --> 00:52:26.313
the officers' actions
reflected their training.

00:52:28.890 --> 00:52:33.600
And that's a true axiom in policing.

00:52:33.600 --> 00:52:35.270
How you train is how you're gonna react.

00:52:35.270 --> 00:52:37.860
So the better we train, the
better understanding we have,

00:52:37.860 --> 00:52:41.223
the better reaction you should
expect and demand from us.

00:52:48.850 --> 00:52:51.330
The mindset of policing
in general has changed

00:52:51.330 --> 00:52:55.490
over the last few years
from this warrior mentality

00:52:55.490 --> 00:53:00.490
of going in and being
the triumphant warrior

00:53:01.905 --> 00:53:04.380
to one of a guardian, one that is

00:53:04.380 --> 00:53:05.900
a caretaker of the community.

00:53:05.900 --> 00:53:08.240
At the San Francisco Police Department,

00:53:08.240 --> 00:53:09.960
we've spent a lot of
time over the last year

00:53:09.960 --> 00:53:12.870
developing a strategy statement,

00:53:12.870 --> 00:53:16.440
and what we came up with,
and this was many members

00:53:16.440 --> 00:53:18.090
of the department that participated is

00:53:18.090 --> 00:53:22.816
we wanna stand for safety
with respect for all, for all,

00:53:22.816 --> 00:53:27.780
disabled or not, typical for all.

00:53:27.780 --> 00:53:31.030
And this our guiding strategy.

00:53:31.030 --> 00:53:32.890
We wanna stand for safety with respect,

00:53:32.890 --> 00:53:34.310
and in order to do that, we have to train,

00:53:34.310 --> 00:53:35.890
we have to understand.

00:53:35.890 --> 00:53:39.840
So part of that strategy includes engaging

00:53:40.755 --> 00:53:43.260
in just, transparent, unbiased,
and responsive policing,

00:53:43.260 --> 00:53:46.460
and again, bias is a big
part of this population.

00:53:46.460 --> 00:53:49.900
There are a lot of biases
in terms of how people view

00:53:49.900 --> 00:53:53.810
people with intellectual and
developmental disabilities.

00:53:53.810 --> 00:53:55.950
We wanna do so in the spirit of dignity

00:53:55.950 --> 00:53:57.510
and collaboration with the community.

00:53:57.510 --> 00:53:59.270
And that's a really important piece.

00:53:59.270 --> 00:54:01.080
That video would not have been produced,

00:54:01.080 --> 00:54:05.050
I know I gave Captain
Moore thanks for this,

00:54:05.050 --> 00:54:06.370
but there are a lot of other people,

00:54:06.370 --> 00:54:08.590
community partners, that made this happen.

00:54:08.590 --> 00:54:11.830
And that had a lot more
to bring to the table

00:54:11.830 --> 00:54:13.910
than we did in terms of expertise.

00:54:13.910 --> 00:54:17.440
So collaboration and partnership is key

00:54:17.440 --> 00:54:22.023
in terms of really
policing getting better.

00:54:22.023 --> 00:54:24.123
And then we wanna maintain and build trust

00:54:25.690 --> 00:54:27.330
and respect as the guardians

00:54:27.330 --> 00:54:29.160
of constitutional human rights.

00:54:29.160 --> 00:54:30.950
And I think that's just very basic,

00:54:30.950 --> 00:54:33.650
but it's really as simple as that for us.

00:54:33.650 --> 00:54:35.450
So how are we gonna accomplish that?

00:54:40.180 --> 00:54:42.150
Training, and what you
see in front of you,

00:54:42.150 --> 00:54:43.610
and I'll go through this part quickly,

00:54:43.610 --> 00:54:47.060
is the San Francisco Police Department's

00:54:47.060 --> 00:54:50.430
level of training compared
to national statistics,

00:54:50.430 --> 00:54:53.130
and I'm proud to say
that our training levels

00:54:53.130 --> 00:54:55.350
are in the orange graphs.

00:54:55.350 --> 00:54:59.850
So we do a lot more than
what's required of us,

00:54:59.850 --> 00:55:03.220
but we do that because we
wanna be better at what we do,

00:55:03.220 --> 00:55:05.172
particularly when it comes to this issue.

00:55:05.172 --> 00:55:07.730
It comes at a cost, though.

00:55:07.730 --> 00:55:09.350
When officers are sitting in training,

00:55:09.350 --> 00:55:12.179
they're not in the field,
and that's this tension

00:55:12.179 --> 00:55:15.470
that everybody wants to deal with now.

00:55:15.470 --> 00:55:17.750
I get calls every day about I wanna see

00:55:17.750 --> 00:55:19.450
more officers in my community.

00:55:19.450 --> 00:55:21.333
What they don't know
is if we don't sit down

00:55:21.333 --> 00:55:23.860
in the academy and do
this type of training,

00:55:23.860 --> 00:55:26.040
the service that you
get is gonna be diluted

00:55:26.040 --> 00:55:27.180
and we could be better.

00:55:27.180 --> 00:55:28.960
So we wanna be responsive,

00:55:28.960 --> 00:55:30.680
but we also wanna be professional,

00:55:30.680 --> 00:55:32.520
and we wanna be the best that we can be

00:55:32.520 --> 00:55:34.650
in terms of handling the calls

00:55:34.650 --> 00:55:37.290
and the community needs
that we need to handle.

00:55:37.290 --> 00:55:40.420
So training is a very, very
important part of that,

00:55:40.420 --> 00:55:42.250
and as you see, I think we really

00:55:42.250 --> 00:55:43.610
put our money where our mouths are

00:55:43.610 --> 00:55:45.010
when it comes to that issue.

00:55:48.010 --> 00:55:50.310
Some of our specialized
training, autism training,

00:55:50.310 --> 00:55:52.397
crisis intervention, procedural justice,

00:55:52.397 --> 00:55:55.650
principled policing and implicit bias,

00:55:55.650 --> 00:55:57.240
managing implicit bias.

00:55:57.240 --> 00:55:58.500
I just signed a memo last night.

00:55:58.500 --> 00:56:00.850
We're about to re-institute another round

00:56:00.850 --> 00:56:01.913
of implicit bias training.

00:56:01.913 --> 00:56:05.280
Creating an inclusive environment,

00:56:05.280 --> 00:56:06.902
just signed that memo last night as well.

00:56:06.902 --> 00:56:09.897
Use of force, and critical thinking.

00:56:09.897 --> 00:56:11.920
Critical thinking is really important,

00:56:11.920 --> 00:56:14.490
because, like I said, a lot of times,

00:56:14.490 --> 00:56:16.940
we get thrust into a
very volatile situation,

00:56:16.940 --> 00:56:20.930
and naturally, you react.

00:56:20.930 --> 00:56:23.470
Some of it is instinctive,
particularly when you feel

00:56:23.470 --> 00:56:27.030
that somebody's life is in
danger, particularly your own.

00:56:27.030 --> 00:56:30.906
You react, and how we
react in that situation

00:56:30.906 --> 00:56:32.570
has to be coordinated.

00:56:32.570 --> 00:56:35.210
So we just instituted
another block of training

00:56:35.210 --> 00:56:37.880
for our troops on critical mindset,

00:56:37.880 --> 00:56:39.240
making sure that we're coordinated,

00:56:39.240 --> 00:56:41.550
and making sure that
we're thinking critically,

00:56:41.550 --> 00:56:44.720
making sure that somebody is
there to slow things down.

00:56:44.720 --> 00:56:46.330
And that is really important,

00:56:46.330 --> 00:56:47.980
particularly when it comes to this issue,

00:56:47.980 --> 00:56:51.503
'cause slowing things down
usually yields better results.

00:56:54.160 --> 00:56:55.197
Our crisis intervention training,

00:56:55.197 --> 00:56:57.110
and I won't go into too
much detail on that,

00:56:57.110 --> 00:57:01.340
but we spend, we have a 40
hour block and a 10 hour block.

00:57:01.340 --> 00:57:04.112
Our goal is to train the
entire police department

00:57:04.112 --> 00:57:05.800
over the next couple years.

00:57:05.800 --> 00:57:09.130
And some of the key issues there:

00:57:09.130 --> 00:57:12.170
de-escalation versus
escalation, voice neutrality,

00:57:12.170 --> 00:57:15.920
listening, tonal
communication atmospheres,

00:57:15.920 --> 00:57:18.180
all of those things when
